Without Multibranch Pipeline (Single Pipeline Job)

Suppose your Git repository has these branches:

JavaWebApp
├── main
├── dev
├── feature-login
├── feature-payment

You create a Pipeline job called:

JavaWebApp-Build

In the job configuration, you specify one branch, for example:

Branch:
main
Workflow
Developer
      │
      ▼
Push code to main
      │
      ▼
Jenkins Pipeline Job
      │
      ▼
Build

If another developer pushes to the dev branch:

dev

Nothing happens because the job is configured only for main.

If you also want to build dev, you need another job:

JavaWebApp-Main
JavaWebApp-Dev
JavaWebApp-FeatureLogin
JavaWebApp-FeaturePayment
Disadvantages
One Jenkins job per branch.
Manual creation of new jobs.
Manual deletion of jobs when branches are removed.
Difficult to manage many feature branches.



With Multibranch Pipeline

Now create one Multibranch Pipeline job:

JavaWebApp

Jenkins scans the repository:

JavaWebApp
├── main
├── dev
├── feature-login
└── feature-payment

Each branch gets its own pipeline automatically.

Workflow
Developer
      │
      ▼
Push to feature-login
      │
      ▼
GitHub Webhook
      │
      ▼
Jenkins scans repository
      │
      ▼
Creates feature-login pipeline
      │
      ▼
Runs Jenkinsfile

No manual job creation is needed.

Real-World Example

Assume a banking application.

Repository:

BankApp
├── main
├── develop
├── release
├── feature-UPI
├── feature-Loans
├── feature-CreditCard
Without Multibranch

You would create:

BankApp-Main
BankApp-Develop
BankApp-Release
BankApp-UPI
BankApp-Loans
BankApp-CreditCard

Every new feature branch requires a new Jenkins job.

If there are 100 feature branches, you would potentially have 100 jobs to manage.

With Multibranch

Only one job exists:

BankApp

Jenkins automatically creates:

BankApp

├── main
├── develop
├── release
├── feature-UPI
├── feature-Loans
└── feature-CreditCard

When feature-UPI is deleted from Git, Jenkins can remove the corresponding branch job during the next scan.



Different Jenkinsfiles Per Branch

One of the biggest advantages is that each branch can have a different Jenkinsfile.


| Feature             | Pipeline Job           | Multibranch Pipeline                            |
| ------------------- | ---------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| Number of jobs      | One per branch         | One parent job for all branches                 |
| New branch          | Manual job creation    | Automatic discovery                             |
| Deleted branch      | Manual cleanup         | Automatic cleanup (with orphaned item strategy) |
| Pull Request builds | Manual or custom setup | Automatic (with GitHub Branch Source)           |
| Jenkinsfile         | One configured branch  | Read from each branch                           |
| Best for            | Single branch projects | GitFlow, feature branches, team development     |

When to Use Each
Use a Pipeline Job when:
The project has only one branch (for example, main).
You have a simple CI/CD workflow.
You're building from a fixed branch.

Examples:

Infrastructure repositories
Utility scripts
Internal automation jobs
Use a Multibranch Pipeline when:
Your team follows GitFlow or feature-branch development.
Developers regularly create feature branches.
You want automatic branch and pull request builds.
Each branch may have its own pipeline logic.

Examples:

Java Spring Boot applications
Node.js applications
Microservices
Enterprise applications with multiple developers



Why do we use a Multibranch Pipeline instead of a normal Pipeline?

Answer:
A normal Pipeline job is tied to a specific branch, so you need separate Jenkins jobs for additional branches. A Multibranch Pipeline automatically discovers branches containing a 
Jenkinsfile, creates and manages branch-specific pipeline jobs, builds pull requests (when integrated with GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket), and cleans up jobs for deleted branches. 
This greatly reduces manual administration and is the preferred approach for projects that use feature branches or GitFlow.
